+
+    (5.4 World-Memory-Driven Behavior is already shipped — meaning tags now drive pawn decisions, cultural drift, and
+    myth formation.)
+
+    ## Key Files You'll Work With
+
+    - scripts/pawn/Pawn.gd (~5200 lines) — pawn behavior, AI dispatch, job claiming
+    - scripts/pawn/PawnData.gd (~2900 lines) — all pawn state, skills, profession
+    - scripts/ai/WorldAI.gd (~3200 lines) — macro AI, neural context builder
+    - scripts/ai/PawnDecisionRuleMatrix.gd — rule-based AI layer
+    - autoloads/WorldMemory.gd — append-only event log
+    - autoloads/WorldMeaning.gd — derived meaning tags
+    - autoloads/SettlementMemory.gd — settlement state, intents, drift
+    - autoloads/SettlementPlanner.gd — building placement, culture
+    - autoloads/KinshipSystem.gd — lineage, family bonds
+    - autoloads/KnowledgeSystem.gd — knowledge transmission (stubby, needs expansion)
+    - autoloads/CulturalMemory.gd — cultural memory
+    - autoloads/GossipPropagation.gd — gossip system
+
+    ## Rules
+
+    1. Read the file before editing. Understand the existing patterns.
+    2. Follow the existing code style: tabs for indentation in .gd files (except SettlementMemory.gd which uses spaces).
+    3. All state changes must derive from tick count. Use WorldRNG for any "random" behavior.
+    4. Record meaningful events to WorldMemory. Derive meaning through WorldMeaning, never hardcode it.
